<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870929-0016 </DOCNO><HL> Valley State, ClosedBy California, to OpenAs Part of Capital Bank---A Wall Street Journal News Roundup</HL><DD> 09/29/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> GOVMTBANKS, THRIFT INSTITUTIONS (BNK)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM) </IN><TEXT>   California bank regulators closed Valley State Bank, Los Angeles, bringing to 136 the number of bank failures nationwide this year.    Howard Gould, the California superintendent of banks, said that significant loan and operating losses had exhausted the bank's capital. The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. said the bank's five offices would reopen today as branches of Capital Bank of California, Los Angeles.    The FDIC said Capital Bank will take over about $76.3 million in 8,800 deposit accounts and secured loans and will purchase $46.7 million in assets of the failed bank. The insurance agency said it would retain assets with a book value of $29.8 million. </TEXT></DOC>